<TITLE> One more gets death in 1993 Mumbai bombings </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MUMBAI, July 20 (Rbdnews24.com/euters) - A man guilty of making vehicle bombs that killed 257 people in India's worst bombings in 1993 was sentenced to death on Friday, making him the seventh person to be handed the capital punishment for the attacks. In all, 13 explosions ripped through several landmarks in the financial capital of Mumbai, including the main stock exchange. Police blamed the attacks on India's most wanted man, Muslim mob boss Dawood Ibrahim. Police say Ibrahim ordered the bombings to avenge the razing of a 16th century mosque by Hindu zealots and ensuing riots in which many Muslims were killed. Mohammed Iqbal Mohammed Yusuf Shaikh was ordered to hang to death by a special anti-terror court sentencing 100 people found guilty in the bombings. Shaikh broke down on hearing his punishment and tried to speak to the judge. But he was led away by policemen. He is the seventh person to be condemned to death, mostly on the charge of preparing the bombs or leaving explosives-laden cars and scooters in busy markets and cinemas. So far the court has sentenced 87 convicts, mostly with varying jail terms and fines for planning and abetting the attacks or for illegal possession of arms. The death sentences still have to be ratified by the Supreme Court. Those sentenced so far include smugglers, petty criminals and a Bollywood producer, as well as policemen and customs officials who took bribes to let the explosives throu
